  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1876, $k081c${"text":"Why is \\(I_1(\\mathrm{N}) > I_1(\\mathrm{O})\\) despite lower \\(Z\\) for N?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"conceptual","block":"p_d_f_block"}$k081c$::jsonb, $k081o$["Half-filled \\(2p^3\\) subshell on N is unusually stable; removing an electron from O gives a half-filled \\(p^3\\) configuration (easier).","Oxygen has smaller atomic radius always in every table.","Ionization energy increases down a group only.","N has more protons than O."]$k081o$::jsonb, 0, $k081e$Extra stability of exactly half-filled \(p\) shell for N.$k081e$),
  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1882, $k082c${"text":"Oxidation state of P in hypophosphorous acid \\(H_3PO_2\\)?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"numerical","block":"p_d_f_block"}$k082c$::jsonb, $k082o$["\\(+1\\)","\\(+3\\)","\\(+5\\)","\\(-3\\)"]$k082o$::jsonb, 0, $k082e$One P=O, two P–H, one P–OH style counting: \(3 + x - 4 = 0 \Rightarrow x = +1\).$k082e$),
  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1888, $k083c${"text":"Why are many \\(Ln^{2+}\\) ions strong **reducing** agents?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"conceptual","block":"p_d_f_block"}$k083c$::jsonb, $k083o$["They tend to lose an electron to reach the very stable \\(+3\\) lanthanide state.","They want to gain electrons to \\(+4\\) always.","\\(+2\\) is always the most stable for all lanthanides.","They oxidize water to \\(O_2\\) instantly only."]$k083o$::jsonb, 0, $k083e$Thermodynamic drive toward dominant +3 oxidation state.$k083e$),
  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1894, $k084c${"text":"\\(XeF_4\\): molecular geometry and lone pairs on Xe?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"numerical","block":"p_d_f_block"}$k084c$::jsonb, $k084o$["**Square planar**, **2** lone pairs on Xe","Tetrahedral, 0 lone pairs","Octahedral, 0 lone pairs","T-shaped, 1 lone pair"]$k084o$::jsonb, 0, $k084e$\(AX_4E_2\); lone pairs axial on octahedral electron geometry → square planar molecular shape.$k084e$),
  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1900, $k085c${"text":"Why is \\(PCl_5\\) known but \\(NCl_5\\) is not a stable analogue?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"conceptual","block":"p_d_f_block"}$k085c$::jsonb, $k085o$["N (period 2) lacks low-energy \\(d\\) orbitals for octet expansion; P uses \\(3d\\) to accommodate five bonds.","Nitrogen is less electronegative.","\\(NCl_5\\) is more stable than \\(PCl_5\\).","Chlorine does not bond to group 15."]$k085o$::jsonb, 0, $k085e$Valence shell expansion for third period and below.$k085e$),
  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1907, $k086c${"text":"Oleum (fuming sulfuric acid) formula from \\(SO_3\\) in concentrated \\(H_2SO_4\\)?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"numerical","block":"p_d_f_block"}$k086c$::jsonb, $k086o$["\\(H_2S_2O_7\\)","\\(H_2SO_5\\) only","\\(SO_3\\) alone","\\(H_2S_3O_{10}\\) only"]$k086o$::jsonb, 0, $k086e$\(H_2SO_4 + SO_3 \rightarrow H_2S_2O_7\).$k086e$),
  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1913, $k087c${"text":"Why do transition metals show many oxidation states but alkali metals almost never do?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"conceptual","block":"p_d_f_block"}$k087c$::jsonb, $k087o$["\\(ns\\) and \\((n-1)d\\) energies are close, so variable \\(d\\) electron loss/participation is possible.","\\(d\\)-block has lower nuclear charge always.","s-block has more \\(d\\) electrons.","Only f-block shows variable oxidation states."]$k087o$::jsonb, 0, $k087e$Similar energies of valence \(s\) and penultimate \(d\) subshells.$k087e$),
  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1919, $k088c${"text":"Unpaired electrons in free \\(Mn^{2+}\\) ion (ground state)?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"numerical","block":"p_d_f_block"}$k088c$::jsonb, $k088o$["\\(5\\)","\\(3\\)","\\(0\\)","\\(2\\)"]$k088o$::jsonb, 0, $k088e$\([Ar]\,3d^5\) after losing \(4s^2\); Hund’s rule → five parallel spins.$k088e$),
  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1925, $k089c${"text":"Why is \\(HI\\) a stronger acid than \\(HF\\) in water (despite F being most electronegative)?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"conceptual","block":"p_d_f_block"}$k089c$::jsonb, $k089o$["Weaker H–X bond (HI) ionizes more readily; bond enthalpy dominates over charge density arguments here.","\\(HF\\) has weaker bond than \\(HI\\).","Electronegativity is irrelevant for any acid strength.","\\(HF\\) never donates protons."]$k089o$::jsonb, 0, $k089e$Bond strength trend in hydrogen halides.$k089e$),
  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1931, $k090c${"text":"Basicity of orthophosphoric acid \\(H_3PO_4\\) (donatable protons on oxygens)?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"numerical","block":"p_d_f_block"}$k090c$::jsonb, $k090o$["**Tribasic** (3)","Monobasic","Dibasic","Tetrabasic"]$k090o$::jsonb, 0, $k090e$Three acidic –OH protons on tetrahedral phosphorus oxoacid.$k090e$),
  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1938, $k091c${"text":"Protein denaturation: why is the **primary** structure (sequence) usually unchanged?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"conceptual","block":"bio_polymers"}$k091c$::jsonb, $k091o$["Peptide (amide) bonds are strong covalent links; denaturation disrupts non-covalent folding and some labile bridges, not the sequence.","Heat always hydrolyzes all peptide bonds instantly.","Primary structure means only disulfide bonds.","Denaturation always cleaves the chain randomly."]$k091o$::jsonb, 0, $k091e$1° structure = amino acid order via covalent peptide bonds.$k091e$),
  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1944, $k092c${"text":"Sucrose is built from which two monosaccharide units (specific anomeric linkage partners)?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"numerical","block":"bio_polymers"}$k092c$::jsonb, $k092o$["\\(\\alpha\\)-D-glucose and \\(\\beta\\)-D-fructose (\\(1\\leftrightarrow2\\) glycosidic bond)","Two glucose only","Galactose and glucose only","Fructose and fructose"]$k092o$::jsonb, 0, $k092e$Non-reducing disaccharide: glucose + fructose at anomeric carbons.$k092e$),
  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1950, $k093c${"text":"Fundamental difference: thermoplastic vs thermosetting polymer?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"conceptual","block":"bio_polymers"}$k093c$::jsonb, $k093o$["Thermosets have a cross-linked 3D covalent network; thermoplastics are largely linear/branched chains that can flow when heated.","Thermoplastics always have more cross-links.","Thermosets melt before flowing always.","Only molecular mass differs."]$k093o$::jsonb, 0, $k093e$Reversibility of melting vs permanent network.$k093e$),
  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1956, $k094c${"text":"Nylon-6,6: how many **carbon atoms per monomer** in adipic acid and in hexamethylenediamine?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"numerical","block":"bio_polymers"}$k094c$::jsonb, $k094o$["**6** carbons in adipic acid and **6** carbons in hexamethylenediamine (the ‘6,6’)","4 and 8","6 and 8","10 and 6"]$k094o$::jsonb, 0, $k094e$Adipic: \(\mathrm{HOOC}(CH_2)_4\mathrm{COOH}\); diamine: \(\mathrm{H_2N}(CH_2)_6\mathrm{NH_2}\) — each contributes six carbons in standard monomer counting for the name.$k094e$),
  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1962, $k095c${"text":"Vitamin C vs Vitamin D regarding **dietary necessity** (typical human biology)?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"conceptual","block":"bio_polymers"}$k095c$::jsonb, $k095o$["Vitamin C must be ingested regularly (water-soluble, not stored well); vitamin D can be synthesized in skin with UV exposure (fat-soluble storage also helps).","Both are synthesized in large amounts in the liver daily.","Neither is ever required from food.","Vitamin D is water-soluble and excreted daily."]$k095o$::jsonb, 0, $k095e$Solubility, storage, and endogenous synthesis differ.$k095e$),
  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1969, $k096c${"text":"Isoelectric point \\(pI\\) for a simple amino acid with \\(pK_{a1}(COOH) = 2.3\\) and \\(pK_{a2}(NH_3^+) = 9.7\\)?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"numerical","block":"bio_polymers"}$k096c$::jsonb, $k096o$["\\(6.0\\)","\\(4.0\\)","\\(12.0\\)","\\(7.4\\)"]$k096o$::jsonb, 0, $k096e$\(pI = (pK_{a1} + pK_{a2})/2\) for neutral side chain.$k096e$),
  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1975, $k097c${"text":"DNA: why A pairs with T and G with C (beyond ‘complementarity’)?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"conceptual","block":"bio_polymers"}$k097c$::jsonb, $k097o$["Purine–pyrimidine pairing keeps helix diameter constant; A–T forms two H-bonds, G–C forms three, matching geometric constraints.","Any base can pair with any base equally well.","Size matching is irrelevant.","Only ionic bonds matter."]$k097o$::jsonb, 0, $k097e$Hydrogen-bond pattern + steric fit in the double helix.$k097e$),
  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1981, $k098c${"text":"Ziegler–Natta HDPE catalyst: two classic components?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"numerical","block":"bio_polymers"}$k098c$::jsonb, $k098o$["\\(TiCl_4\\) and triethylaluminum (e.g. \\(Al(C_2H_5)_3\\))","\\(Ni(CO)_4\\) and \\(H_2SO_4\\)","\\(Pt\\) and \\(H_2\\)","\\(Fe\\) and \\(CuSO_4\\)"]$k098o$::jsonb, 0, $k098e$Organometallic co-catalyst + transition-metal halide for coordinated polymerization.$k098e$),
  ('academic', 'chemistry', 1987, $k099c${"text":"What is an **analgesic**, and how do non-narcotic vs narcotic types differ in broad terms?","pack":"puc_chemistry_jee_neet_100","qtype":"conceptual","block":"bio_polymers"}$k099c$::jsonb, $k099o$["Analgesics reduce pain; non-narcotics (e.g. NSAIDs) often act peripherally/anti-inflammatory, narcotics (e.g. morphine) act centrally with addiction risk.","Analgesics cause unconsciousness always.","Only antibiotics are analgesics.","Narcotic and non-narcotic are identical mechanisms."]$k099o$::jsonb, 0, $k099e$Pain relief without general anesthesia by definition for simple analgesia.$k099e$),
